<!-- HERO -->
   <section class="bg-[linear-gradient(120deg,rgba(11,17,32,.92),rgba(17,24,39,.85)),url(&#39;https://legalx24.com/img/ibc-hero.jpg&#39;)]  bg-cover bg-center text-white text-center px-5 py-[120px]"> 
      <h1 class="font-black text-[clamp(36px,4vw,52px)]"> Insolvency &amp; Bankruptcy Code (IBC) </h1> 
      <p class="max-w-[950px] mx-auto mt-4 text-[17.5px] leading-[1.85]"> The Insolvency and Bankruptcy Code, 2016 (IBC) is a comprehensive legislation that consolidates and amends laws relating to insolvency resolution of corporate persons, partnership firms, and individuals in a time-bound and structured manner. </p> </section> 
   <section class="py-[60px] px-5 bg-white container mx-auto"> 
      <h2 class="font-extrabold text-[clamp(26px,3vw,36px)] text-[#0b1120] mb-3 after:content-[&#39;&#39;] after:block after:w-[70px] after:h-[4px] after:bg-amber-500 after:mt-2"> Introduction to IBC </h2> 
      <p class="text-[16px] text-[#374151] leading-[1.9] mb-3"> The IBC was enacted to address the growing challenge of non-performing assets and financial distress in the Indian economy. It provides a unified framework for resolution of insolvency while balancing the interests of creditors, debtors, and stakeholders. </p> 
      <p class="text-[16px] text-[#374151] leading-[1.9]"> The Code emphasizes time-bound resolution, maximization of asset value, and promotion of entrepreneurship by providing a clear exit mechanism for failing businesses. </p> </section> 
   <section class="py-[60px] px-5 bg-[#f9fafb] container mx-auto"> 
      <h2 class="font-extrabold text-[clamp(26px,3vw,36px)] text-[#0b1120] mb-3 after:content-[&#39;&#39;] after:block after:w-[70px] after:h-[4px] after:bg-amber-500 after:mt-2"> Corporate Insolvency Resolution Process (CIRP) </h2> 
      <p class="text-[16px] text-[#374151] leading-[1.9] mb-3"> Under IBC, financial creditors, operational creditors, or the corporate debtor itself may initiate insolvency proceedings before the National Company Law Tribunal (NCLT). </p> 
      <p class="text-[16px] text-[#374151] leading-[1.9]"> Upon admission, a moratorium is imposed, and an Insolvency Resolution Professional (IRP) is appointed to manage the affairs of the corporate debtor. </p> 
      <div class="bg-white border-l-[6px] border-amber-500 p-[26px] rounded-[10px] my-[28px] shadow-[0_18px_40px_rgba(0,0,0,.08)] font-semibold"> The primary objective of CIRP is resolution, not liquidation, ensuring revival of viable businesses wherever possible. </div> </section> 
   <section class="py-[60px] px-5 bg-white container mx-auto"> 
      <div class="row items-center">
         <div class="col-lg-6">
            <h2 class="font-extrabold text-[clamp(26px,3vw,36px)] text-[#0b1120] mb-3 after:content-[&#39;&#39;] after:block after:w-[70px] after:h-[4px] after:bg-amber-500 after:mt-2"> Role of NCLT &amp; Insolvency Professionals </h2>
            <p class="text-[16px] text-[#374151] leading-[1.9] mb-3"> The National Company Law Tribunal (NCLT) acts as the adjudicating authority for corporate insolvency matters under IBC. </p>
            <p class="text-[16px] text-[#374151] leading-[1.9] mb-3"> Insolvency Professionals play a crucial role in managing the debtor&#39;s affairs, verifying claims, and facilitating resolution plans approved by the Committee of Creditors. </p>
            <p class="text-[16px] text-[#374151] leading-[1.9]"> The resolution plan, once approved, becomes binding on all stakeholders. </p>
         </div>
         <div class="col-lg-6"> 
            <img src="https://legalx24.com/img/ibc-1.jpg" class="w-full rounded-[14px] shadow-[0_20px_45px_rgba(0,0,0,.22)]" alt="IBC Proceedings NCLT" data-themekey="#"/> &#160;</div>
      </div> </section> 
   <section class="bg-gradient-to-br from-[#0b1120] to-[#111827] text-white py-[60px] px-5"> 
      <div class="container mx-auto">
         <h2 class="font-extrabold text-[clamp(26px,3vw,36px)] mb-3"> Liquidation Process under IBC </h2>
         <p class="text-[16px] leading-[1.9] mb-3"> If resolution is not achieved within the prescribed timeline, the corporate debtor may enter liquidation. Assets are realized and distributed as per statutory waterfall mechanism. </p>
         <p class="text-[16px] leading-[1.9]"> The liquidation process ensures transparent and equitable distribution of proceeds among creditors. </p>
      </div> </section> 
   <section class="py-[60px] px-5 bg-white container mx-auto"> 
      <h2 class="font-extrabold text-[clamp(26px,3vw,36px)] text-[#0b1120] mb-3 after:content-[&#39;&#39;] after:block after:w-[70px] after:h-[4px] after:bg-amber-500 after:mt-2"> Rights of Financial &amp; Operational Creditors </h2> 
      <p class="text-[16px] text-[#374151] leading-[1.9] mb-3"> Financial creditors participate in the Committee of Creditors (CoC) and have voting rights on resolution plans. </p> 
      <p class="text-[16px] text-[#374151] leading-[1.9]"> Operational creditors are entitled to fair treatment and protection under approved resolution plans. </p> </section> 
   <section class="py-[60px] px-5 bg-[#f9fafb] container mx-auto"> 
      <h2 class="font-extrabold text-[clamp(26px,3vw,36px)] text-[#0b1120] mb-3 after:content-[&#39;&#39;] after:block after:w-[70px] after:h-[4px] after:bg-amber-500 after:mt-2"> Importance of Legal Strategy in IBC Proceedings </h2> 
      <p class="text-[16px] text-[#374151] leading-[1.9] mb-3"> IBC matters involve strict statutory timelines, complex financial documentation, and strategic negotiations among stakeholders. </p> 
      <p class="text-[16px] text-[#374151] leading-[1.9]"> Professional legal guidance ensures compliance, protection of interests, and effective representation before NCLT. </p> </section> 
